<br>
the problem with cliches is that they are easy to fall into. the trick is to spin them in a new way. take for instance The Sixth Day (with Ahnuld Schwartzenegger). the cliche is a man fighting to get his life back and the spin, the life he's fighting to get back isn't his. (well, it belongs to one of them, but the other guy doesn't realize until pretty late that he's the clone, not the original.) now, while the film itself may not be stellar the concept is very cool (one that could have really been developed well if Hollywood weren't a bunch of weenies.) <br>
<br>
unfortunately, you'll probably never be able to break out of the cliches. they say there are only seven storylines in existence anyway, everything is just a variation of one of the seven. what you'll have to do (what every good writer does) is take something standard and do the unexpected. depending on the genre the unexpected could be any number of things. <br>
<br>
for instance: boy meets girl. (okay, that's simple and been done a thousand times.) boy is a med student who meets girl (a cancer patient) while doing his residency. only, maybe she doesn't really have cancer. or maybe she's a psych patient. or he's a psych patient who has a message from God (or aliens) and she's dying of cancer and figures she has nothing to lose by helping him, etc. etc. etc.<br>
<br>
that's not the best example but it gave me an idea for something interesting. maybe insane people are actually more evolved and can see a different plane of reality, one that's so advanced they can't communicate it to others. then take that as the starting point and go back to boy meets girl. <br>
<br>
the key to breaking a cliche open is finding something that you think is interesting and then taking a cliche and working the interesting bit into it (or vice versa). the problem is it takes lots of practice. read lots of stuff from National Geographic articles to the worst sci-fi/fantasy you can get your hands on. the more you read the more capable you become of writing well and writing originally. <br>
<br>
