<br>
If you've seen that movie and then read the story you would have no idea that I'd just stolen almost an entire story. Its my way of dealing with writers block. Coming up with something new from something used already. Try it. Even if you don't have writers block. You'll be surprised at how you can see things if you force yourself to look to hard. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pencilsoldier>Pencil Soldier</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/11/03 9:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1026.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.freewebs.com/pencilsoldier/pencils.txt  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:  Re: A walk around Ye Olde Writers' Block</span><hr size=1> Read the book Charecters and Viewpoint by Orson Scott Card. That will help so much you have no idea. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><br>
